SIMPLE: wonder
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wonder
<hw>Won"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wonder</ets>, <ets>wunder</ets>, AS. <ets>wundor</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>wonder</ets>, OS. <ets>wundar</ets>, OHG. <ets>wuntar</ets>, G.
<ets>wunder</ets>, Icel. <ets>undr</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>under</ets>,
and perhaps to Gr. <?/ to gaze at.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That emotion which is excited by novelty, or the
presentation to the sight or mind of something new, unusual, strange,
great, extraordinary, or not well understood; surprise; astonishment;
admiration; amazement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were filled with <qex>wonder</qex> and amazement at that
which had happened unto him.</q> <rj><qau>Acts iii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wonder</qex> is the effect of novelty upon ignorance.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Wonder</xex> expresses less than
<xex>astonishment</xex>, and much less than <xex>amazement</xex>. It
differs from <xex>admiration</xex>, as now used, in not being
necessarily accompanied with love, esteem, or approbation.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cause of wonder; that which excites surprise; a
strange thing; a prodigy; a miracle.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ Babylon, the
<xex>wonder</xex> of all tongues.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To try things oft, and never to give over, doth
<qex>wonders</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am as a <qex>wonder</qex> unto many.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxxi.
7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Seven wonders of the world</b></col>. <cd>See in the
Dictionary of Noted Names in Fiction.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wonder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wonder
<hw>Won"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wondered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wondering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wundrian</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be affected with surprise or admiration; to be
struck with astonishment; to be amazed; to marvel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could not sufficiently <qex>wonder</qex> at the intrepidity of
these diminutive mortals.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We cease to <qex>wonder</qex> at what we understand.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel doubt and curiosity; to wait with uncertain
expectation; to query in the mind; <as>as, he <ex>wondered</ex> why they
came</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>wonder</qex>, in my soul,⟦br⟧
What you would ask me, that I should deny.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wonder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wonder
<hw>Won"der</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Wonderful.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After that he said a <qex>wonder</qex> thing.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wonder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wonder
<hw>Won"der</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Wonderfully.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wondered</ent>⟦br⟧
